Implement JDBC for Database Connectivity

JDBC is implemented in the project to allow the Java program to connect with the database and perform operations such as storing passwords,
retrieving data, or updating records. Implementing JDBC ensures that the application communicates smoothly with the backend database using SQL queries.


import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;
import java.sql.PreparedStatement;

public class DBHelper {

    public static Connection connect() {
        try {
            String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/passworddb";
            String user = "root";
            String pass = "";

            return DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, pass);

        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Connection Error: " + e.getMessage());
            return null;
        }
    }
}

class PasswordService {

    public void savePassword(String password) {
        try {
            Connection con = DBHelper.connect();

            String sql = "INSERT INTO passwords(password) VALUES(?)";
            PreparedStatement ps = con.prepareStatement(sql);
            ps.setString(1, password);

            ps.executeUpdate();
            con.close();

            System.out.println("Password stored successfully!");

        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error while saving: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}




Summary

JDBC is implemented by connecting to the database using DriverManager, running SQL commands through PreparedStatement, handling errors safely,
and closing the connection after completing the operations. This ensures reliable and secure communication between the Java application and the database.






